defaultWritten evidence from the Student Law Think Tank, Northumbria University (CRJ 04)
default&#xa0;
defaultForeword
default&#xa0;defaultBackgrounddefault1.
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultThis document is a response to the Political and Constitutional Reform Committee’s consultation about the role of the judiciary if there were a codified constitution.
default It was produced by Northumbria University’s Student Law Think Tank, which is a School of Law student society. The aim of the Student Law Think Tank is to involve students with policy work and get students’ voices heard across society. 
default&#xa0;
defaultAimsdefault2.
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultThe aim of this document was for Northumbria University School of Law students to take up the invitation to contribute to the debate about the role of the judiciary if there were a codified constitution.  Whilst some staff 
defaultwere
default involved in helping the proj
defaultect come to fruition the content of the response is entirely the work of the students.  
default&#xa0;
default3.
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultThis Student Law Think Tank decided to focus upon question 3 of the consultation:
default&#xa0;
defaultIf the UK were to have a codified constitution, what powers should the courts have 
defaultif they held that a piece of legislation was unconstitutional?
default&#xa0;
defaulta)
default&#xa0;
defaultWhat would be the implications of these powers on existing constitutional doctrines, including parliamentary sovereignty and judicial review?
default&#xa0;
defaultb)
default&#xa0;
defaultIn the context of question 3, what can we
default learn from the interaction between the UK courts and the European Court of Justice and European Court of Human Rights?
default&#xa0;
defaultApproachdefault4.
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultThe comments below were collected over a series of large group meetings over the course of three weeks in which the contents of the response were questioned and debated.  This document is the work of 
default22 students.
default  It takes into account the opinions of all 
defaultof the contributors to the response, and although it has been edited and reformatted, it aims to record both the areas of consensus which were reached as well as reflecting the areas where divergence of opinion emerged. 
default&#xa0;
defaultChapter 1: Summary of Evidence 
default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;
default5.
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultThe following are the conclusions of the Student Law Think Tank:
default&#xa0;
defaulti)
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultThe Courts should have the two key powers to declare legislation invalid or incompatible allowing for challenge before and after implementation. 
defaultii)
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultThat the senior Courts (specifically High 
defaultCourt and above) would be able to exercise the two powers.
defaultiii)
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultA separate constitutional court was not favoured.
defaultiv)
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultThat the decisions made in relation to the constitutional validity or compatibility of a piece of legislation would be done by a super majority dec
defaultision and that only single judgments would be given for clarity. 
defaultv)
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultThat there would be an effect on existing constitutional doctrines such as parliamentary supremacy.
defaultvi)
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultThere were distinct advantages from copying and learning from the approaches adopted by th
defaulte European Court of Justice and the European Court of Human Rights in dealing with and 
defaultmanaging constitutional issues.
