defaultChapter 
default4
default: Response to question 3b
default&#xa0;
default28.
default&#xa0; 
defaultThe m
defaultembers 
defaultdiscussed numerous reference points in this area
default, for example
default,
default single judgments
default 
defaultfrom the European institutions. The following were discussed
default the most:
defaulti.
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultIf a
default Constitutional Court
default was
default introduced to the UK, 
defaultshould 
defaultspecialist chambers be formed within it to assure judgments remained clear and properly informed?
defaultii.
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultIf, like in the USA, it was made very difficult to alter the constitution itself, how would the UK cope
default with European directives etc
default.
default and associated timelines?
default&#xa0;
default29.
default&#xa0; 
defaultIt was noted that now might be the best time to codify the UK constitution, given the amount of guidance we have already gained from the European institutions, both on EU law and the law of human ri
defaultghts. Some members felt that codifying the UK constitution and entrenching it would create the potential for conflict with the European institutions in situations where the UK constitution was itself incompatible with the European Convention on Human Right
defaults or EU Law. By definition the content of the constitution would be much more difficult to change than traditional statute law. One suggestion for preventing such problems was to include a system of fast-tracking the concerns of the EU and the Convention w
defaulthereby changes to the UK constitution necessary to comply with the European institutions could be made much more quickly.
default 
defaultAll other EU countries and members of the Council of Europe have written constitutions and as such there could be much to learn from t
defaultheir approaches on this issue. 
